definitions.definition: The set of letters used when writing in a language .
examples: The Greek alphabet has only twenty-four letters.
In the first year of school, pupils are taught to recite the alphabet .

definitions.definition: A writing system in which letters represent phonemes . ( Contrast e.g. logography , a writing system in which each character represents a word, and syllabary , in which each character represents a syllable. )

subdefinitions.definition: A writing system in which there are letters for the consonant and vowel phonemes . ( Contrast e.g. abjad . )

definitions.definition: A typically finite set of distinguishable symbols .
examples: Let L {\displaystyle L} be a regular language over the alphabet Σ {\displaystyle \Sigma } .

definitions.definition: An individual letter of an alphabet; an alphabetic character.
An agent of the FBI , the CIA , or another such government agency.
